{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59394e1d-018b-4feb-ac6d-6d963015a90c","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (use a library like `ModelContextProtocol` / `McpDotNet`).\n- **Don't** write logs or diagnostics to stdout — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol stream.\n- If you publish the server as a tool, replace `dotnet run --project ...` with the path to the built executable.\n\nFor a **published/self-contained** build, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"67a701f5-235f-457e-9047-c13ad287771a","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"8435:2AC8C6:F3C73E:134BFEA:69FFDABF"},"id":"d8d5f837-d724-4702-bc1c-754c0d3606a3","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:29.472Z","parentId":"07cc9d43-f0b6-48e6-a04c-de71d089199b"}
